Q4. Comparison with buck and boost at the same operating point:
All three converters designed for the same: V_in=12V, V_out(magnitude)=12V (unity gain for buck-boost), I_load=2A, f_s=100kHz, L=50µH.
(a) Buck: D=1 for 12V output from 12V input. What does D=1 mean physically? Can a buck converter achieve unity gain in practice?
(b) Boost: D=0 for 12V output from 12V input. What does D=0 mean? Can a boost achieve unity gain?
(c) Buck-boost: D=0.5 for unity gain. Find I_L_avg, I_peak, switch voltage stress.
(d) Compare the switch voltage stress of buck-boost (V_in+|V_out|=24V) with buck (V_in=12V) and boost (V_out=12V) for this unity-gain case. The buck-boost has 2× the switch stress at unity gain — why is this a disadvantage?
(e) For a practical battery application where V_in varies 8V to 16V and V_out=12V is needed: which topologies can handle the full range? Show by finding D at V_in=8V and V_in=16V for each topology (buck, boost, buck-boost) and identifying which D values are outside the practical range.
Q5. Loss analysis and efficiency at different operating points:
Buck-boost: V_in=9V, I_load=2A, f_s=200kHz. MOSFET R_DS(on)=40mΩ, diode V_f=0.5V, inductor R_L=30mΩ.
Calculate efficiency at three operating points:
(a) |V_out|=6V (stepping down): find D, I_L_avg, compute total losses (MOSFET conduction + diode conduction + inductor copper), and efficiency
(b) |V_out|=9V (unity gain): repeat
(c) |V_out|=18V (stepping up): repeat
(d) At which operating point is efficiency lowest? Explain why in terms of how I_L_avg changes with V_out (since I_L_avg=I_load/(1-D) and D increases as V_out increases relative to V_in)
(e) This efficiency dependence on conversion ratio is a fundamental characteristic of all non-isolated converters. What does it imply for converter design when you need a very high step-up or step-down ratio?
